---

## Why This Configuration — The Full Reasoning

### The Core Finding: OBS Disables Network Optimizations Under RTMPS

This is the single most important fact in this document.

**OBS Studio is hard-coded to disable the "Enable network optimizations" setting whenever the stream service is RTMPS (TLS-encrypted RTMP over port 443).** The checkbox in OBS Advanced → Network does nothing under RTMPS. When connecting to an RTMPS endpoint, OBS writes this line to the log:

```
[rtmp stream: 'adv_stream'] Disabling network optimizations, not compatible with RTMPS
```

This is verified behavior, confirmed in the OBS source code and on the OBS forum. The OBS log file `2026-04-18_00-41-08.txt` line 340 and line 370 both contain this exact message from the last RTMPS test attempt.

**Consequence when network optimizations are disabled:** OBS does not enlarge the TCP socket send buffer beyond the Windows default, which is 64 KB (65,536 bytes) on a 1 Gbps NIC.

**Consequence of a 64 KB send buffer on a high-latency streaming connection:** TCP slow-start has too little window room to absorb bursty NVENC keyframes. During the first 3–5 minutes of a stream, the connection drops hundreds to thousands of frames while TCP congestion control tries to find a sustainable sending rate. The Windows TCP stack eventually auto-tunes the send buffer upward (observed growing to 4 MB by end of stream), but by then thousands of frames have already been lost.

### The Diagnostic Evidence

Three streams confirmed the pattern:

| Stream | Protocol | Socket send buffer at start | Final dropped frames |
|---|---|---|---|
| MM09 (April 12) | RTMP via Restream → Frankfurt | 65,536 bytes | 37.2% |
| MM10 (April 14) | RTMP via Restream → Frankfurt | 65,536 bytes | 43.5% |
| Test (April 18, RTMPS) | Direct RTMPS to YouTube | 65,536 bytes | 8.3% (all front-loaded) |
| **Test (April 18, plain RTMP)** | **Direct RTMP to YouTube** | **1,048,576 bytes (expected)** | **0% — verified across entire test stream** |

The first three streams all showed the same drop pattern: heavy dropped frames at the start of the stream, tapering as the TCP send buffer auto-tuned upward. The MM09 and MM10 streams did not have "Enable network optimizations" checked, so the buffer stayed small throughout the multi-hour session. The April 18 RTMPS test had the checkbox enabled but it had no effect — confirmed by the log line quoted above.

The final test on April 18 used plain RTMP (not RTMPS) with the same checkbox enabled. The result: zero dropped frames for the entire test duration. This is the working configuration.

### Why Plain RTMP Instead of RTMPS

YouTube supports both RTMP (port 1935, unencrypted) and RTMPS (port 443, TLS-encrypted) ingest. The only functional difference is encryption. On a trusted home network, the RTMP stream key is sent in plaintext during the handshake — a low-risk tradeoff in practice for most streamers on residential connections.

Plain RTMP ingest URL for YouTube: `rtmp://a.rtmp.youtube.com/live2`
RTMPS ingest URL for YouTube: `rtmps://a.rtmps.youtube.com/live2`

Plain RTMP is the correct choice here because OBS's "Enable network optimizations" only applies to plain RTMP. That setting is what enlarges the TCP send buffer to 1 MB, which is what eliminates the drop burst.

### Why OBS Does Not Expose a "YouTube - RTMP" Preset

OBS's service list shows "YouTube - RTMPS" and "YouTube - HLS" but does not include a plain RTMP preset. The plain RTMP option was removed from the preset list at some point, presumably to encourage encryption. The Custom service option is how plain RTMP is configured manually. This is not a bug or workaround — it is the supported configuration path.

### Why 4500 kbps (Not 6000)

The Athens connection's upload capacity measured at 8.6 Mbps at time of testing (versus 19 Mbps rated). Community best practice is to keep streaming bitrate below 70% of available upload to allow headroom for TCP retransmissions, keyframe bursts, and momentary network fluctuations.

- 6000 kbps = 70% utilization of 8.6 Mbps (near upper safe limit)
- 4500 kbps = 52% utilization of 8.6 Mbps (comfortable headroom)

4500 kbps is the conservative choice. YouTube's recommended bitrate for 1080p30 is 4500 kbps, so this is exactly on YouTube's target for this resolution and framerate. Quality impact is minimal for writing content where most of the frame is static text.

This bitrate may be increased to 6000 kbps when back in the US on a more capable connection. For now, 4500 kbps is the right value.

### Why 30 FPS (Not 60)

The primary content is writing in iA Writer — mostly static text with occasional cursor movement and camera footage of the writer. 60 fps produces no perceptible quality improvement for this content type while doubling the data rate. Dropping to 30 fps reduces encoding load and gives TCP more headroom per frame to recover from any hiccup.

### Why CBR (Not CQP or VBR)

Live streaming platforms expect a stable bitrate for transcoding and distribution. CBR (Constant Bitrate) maintains a predictable data rate, which makes TCP behavior more predictable and reduces the chance of bursts overwhelming the send buffer. YouTube's ingest recommendation is CBR for live streams.

### Why NVENC (Not x264)

The AERO X16 has an RTX 5070 Laptop GPU with a single NVENC encoder. NVENC offloads encoding from CPU to GPU. This frees CPU for OBS's other work (scene compositing, audio mixing, filters) and produces encoding quality on par with x264 Medium preset at P5 (the OBS-recommended balance).

### Why Keyframe Interval = 2 Seconds

YouTube requires keyframes every 2 seconds (or 4 seconds maximum) for live streaming. 2 seconds is the standard choice — it enables better seeking and lower-latency playback for viewers. Lower keyframe intervals increase data rate; higher intervals increase seek latency. 2 seconds is the sweet spot.

### Why "Enable network optimizations" Must Stay Checked

With the Custom service set to plain RTMP, this checkbox now actually does what its name implies. It tells OBS to increase the TCP socket send buffer at stream start to 1 MB (up from the 64 KB Windows default). This is the mechanism that eliminated the drop burst. Unchecking it would revert the stream to the same failing behavior seen in MM09 and MM10.

### Why Twitch Is Suspended (For Now)

Historical data: Twitch contributed approximately 2 live viewers out of 26 on MM10. Some Twitch chat activity was from viewer-sale bots, not real viewers. Simulcasting to Twitch during the Athens stay was requiring Restream as a relay, which added a Frankfurt hop and its own ingest characteristics — complicating diagnostics without delivering meaningful audience value.

When back in the US, Twitch will be relaunched using **Aitum Multistream**, a free OBS plugin that handles simulcast locally without a third-party relay. The RTX 5070's single NVENC encoder can handle 2× 1080p H.264 outputs simultaneously. This eliminates Restream entirely and keeps both YouTube and Twitch connections under OBS's direct control.

